#Firmware
So, to make sure that my board was recognized by the compiler and everything worked properly, I had to edit Arduino IDE's code files to accommodate my board and its pin layout. Follow this to make sure your board is recognized as well!
Step-by-step guide to make your custom RP2040 board recognized and programmable in Arduino IDE
You’ve got the pin map and board entry—now here’s the clean, end-to-end workflow to implement it and verify everything works.

Prerequisites
Arduino IDE installed (v2.x recommended).

Earle Philhower RP2040 core installed via Board Manager.

Your RP2040 board wired for USB UF2 (BOOTSEL, USB D+/D−, 3V3/1V1 rails, crystal or internal clock).

Install the RP2040 core
Open Arduino IDE → File → Preferences.

In Additional Board Manager URLs, add:

Code
"https://github.com/earlephilhower/arduino-pico/releases/download/global/package_rp2040_index.json"
Go to Tools → Board → Board Manager.

Search for RP2040 and install “Raspberry Pi RP2040 Boards by Earle Philhower”.

Locate the core files
Windows:

C:\Users<You>\AppData\Local\Arduino15\packages\rp2040\hardware\arduino-pico<version>\

macOS/Linux:

~/.arduino15/packages/rp2040/hardware/arduino-pico//

You’ll find boards.txt and the variants/ folder here. The .arduino15 directory is hidden—enable “show hidden files.”

Create your custom variant
In .../variants/, create a new folder: myboard.

Inside myboard, create pins_arduino.h and paste this:
"
cpp
#pragma once

// ===== LED =====
#define PINLED 25
#ifndef LEDBUILTIN
#define LEDBUILTIN PINLED
#endif

// ===== UART (Serial1) =====
#define PINSERIALTX 0 // J1 TX → GPIO0
#define PINSERIALRX 1 // J1 RX → GPIO1

// ===== I2C (Wire) =====
#define PINWIRESDA 8 // J1 SDA → GPIO8
#define PINWIRESCL 9 // J1 SCL → GPIO9

// ===== SPI =====
#define PINSPISCK 2 // J1 SCK → GPIO2
#define PINSPIMOSI 3 // J1 MOSI → GPIO3
#define PINSPIMISO 4 // J1 MISO → GPIO4
#define PINSPICS 5 // J1 CS → GPIO5

// ===== ADC channels =====
#define PINA0 26 // J1 ADC0 → GPIO26
#define PINA1 27 // J1 ADC1 → GPIO27
#define PIN_A2 28 // J1 ADC2 → GPIO28

// ===== Debug pins =====
#define PINSWCLK 24 // SWCLK → GPIO24
#define PINSWDIO 25 // SWDIO → GPIO25

// ===== Connector aliases =====
#define PINJ1TX 0
#define PINJ1RX 1
#define PINJ1SCK 2
#define PINJ1MOSI 3
#define PINJ1MISO 4
#define PINJ1CS 5
#define PINJ1SDA 8
#define PINJ1SCL 9
#define PINJ1ADC0 26
#define PINJ1ADC1 27
#define PINJ1ADC2 28

// ===== Default interfaces =====
#define SERIALPORTMONITOR Serial
#define SERIALPORTHARDWARE Serial1
"
Add your board to boards.txt
Open .../boards.txt.

Append this block at the end:
"
txt
##############################################################

myboard.name=My Custom RP2040 Board
myboard.build.core=rp2040
myboard.build.variant=myboard
myboard.upload.maximumsize=2097152
myboard.upload.maximumdatasize=262144
myboard.upload.protocol=rp2040
myboard.build.fcpu=133000000L
myboard.build.usbproduct="Custom RP2040"
myboard.build.usbmanufacturer="ShauryaLabs"
"
Save the file.

Restart Arduino IDE and select your board
Close and reopen Arduino IDE.

Go to Tools → Board and select My Custom RP2040 Board.

Choose the correct Port (or use BOOTSEL mode for UF2 upload).
